Scientists have found a way to detect related stars.
Astrophysicists at the University of California in Santa Cruz have studied turbulence and its effect on chemical homogeneity in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of experts will allow for the search of related stars, i.e., from a single cluster.
The results of their research have been published in Nature magazine and are available briefly on the university website.
The reason for the same chemical composition of the nearby stars is the turbulence in the clouds of gas prior to the formation of the stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the star cluster, its chemical composition can determine the place of birth and the region of formation of the next-of-kin stars.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
Modelling results from astrophysicists show that such differences should not emerge.
In their research, supercomputer experts simulated two interstellar gas streams that formed a cloud together.
For several million years, this object has been transformed by its own gravity into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
Scientists added markings to the original gas streams and found that rapid turbulence caused a high degree of chemical homogeneity in the cloud.
Astrophysicists believe that their research proves that it is possible to search for chemically related stars, as well as to identify possible regions of the formation of such objects.
