Recalling the very American ideal that labour rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed a bill that protects the organization of trade unions as a civil right.
"Where unions are, there are middle-class jobs," says Allison, the Minnesota Democrat, who is co-chair of the Congress of Progressive Fraction.
That's why I'm proud to introduce the Workers Empowerment Act with the Civil Rights Movement symbol John Lewis.
This innovative bill will provide workers with the same legal opportunities to discriminate against trade union organizations as other forms of discrimination by stopping the forces of trade union opponents.
The amendment of the Labour Regulation Act in such a way as to allow workers who face discrimination for their association with trade unions to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive damages and punitive payments - is a reasonable and necessary initiative.
But this is certainly not a radical initiative, at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to figure out what Allison, Lewis, and the co-authors of the bill are to remember a very American idea.
Despite the attacks on trade unions in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states throughout the country - Americans once supported countries around the world in accepting, expanding and respecting labour rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when that country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after the Second World War, General Douglas McArthur and his associates helped the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that Hideki Tojo’s paramilitary autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their trade unions played a role in shaping the new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that “the right of workers to organize, to negotiate and to collective action is guaranteed”.
When the United States occupied Germany after the Second World War, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his assistants helped the Germans to write a constitution that guaranteed that Adolf Hitler’s fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to be organized and heard in the new State, the Germans included an article that stated openly: “The right to form associations to protect and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and every profession or field of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe this right will have no legal effect; measures to that end will be declared illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was Chairman of the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the World Declaration on Human Rights to be adopted in 1948 by the United Nations as a world agreement, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that “everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions to protect his interests”.
For generations, Americans have taken due note of the basic provision that labour rights are human rights.
When the country consulted other countries on how to build civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions - and to have the union participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies - should be protected.
Now that these rights are being attacked in America, it is wise indeed to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said 50 years ago,
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the union movement did not undermine the nation's strength, but increased it.
By raising the standard of living of millions, trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and raised an entire nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers how it should be for us.
Formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and extension of civil rights protection to prevent discrimination against the organization of trade unions - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are reviving the ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
The judge is temporarily blocking a law that could shut down all abortion clinics in Louisiana.
In the United States, a federal judge temporarily blocked the enactment of Louisiana's law on Sunday, which his supporters say is likely to close down all five abortion clinics in the state.
Under this measure, which was signed for execution by the Governor of Louisiana, Bobby Jinadl, in June and was due to enter into force on 1 September, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have the authority to receive patients in a hospital within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge ' s decision meant that doctors could now continue to perform legal abortions while continuing to seek such authority.
“The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally while continuing to act on their credentials,” wrote Judge John de Gravelles in his decision.
A hearing will be scheduled within a month during which the judge will render a more permanent decision on the Act.
Advocates of the right to abortion welcomed this decision, the latest in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying that it would give doctors more time to obtain hospital authority.
“Today's decision guarantees that Louisiana's women will be protected from a insidious law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights”, said Nancy Northap, president and head of the Center for Reproductive Rights, who filed a motion to suspend the law on behalf of three out of five state clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applied to doctors from the two clinics who had not filed a complaint in the case and also applied for admission.
Louisiana is in the 11 states that have enacted such laws, and the courts have recently found such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of the Texas law, which would have shut down most of the remaining clinics in the state, were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Advocates of the right to abortion, together with the American College of Obstetrics and Gynaecologists and the American Medical Association, say that admission laws impose medically unnecessary restrictions on doctors.
Opponents of abortion argue that such measures are aimed at protecting women ' s health, although some have also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who aborts in Louisiana has the authority to receive at the hospital, as reported by the Center for Reproductive Rights.
If all other doctors in the state were to be forced to stop doing this procedure, the doctor, fearing for his safety, would have stopped doing the procedure, the team informed.
In criticizing this decision, Louisiana officials said that they would not punish abortion doctors while their applications for admission were awaiting a decision.
