Experts are of the view that the introduction of quotas on domestic products would facilitate import substitution and could speed up the process.
However, this initiative alone will not lead to import substitution, as it requires a set of measures, Litvinenko is certain.
In any case, 50 per cent of the goods sold under the initiative could still be imported from abroad, which meant that no full replacement would take place, but significant steps in that direction would be taken.
In addition, there are few quotas, and there is still a need for domestic production to meet these quotas.
These quotas will provide such guarantees”, the expert notes.
Untimely diagnosed and lack of access to optimal treatment means that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James published a video of the memory of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who forgive in rural Australia face a higher risk of mortality from ovarian cancer than those living in urban areas.
Researchers analysed the disease maps of over 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that only 35% had lived five years after being diagnosed.
Chief researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Institute of Medical Research reported that the probability of dying during the study was 20 percent higher for those living in regions and remote areas of the state than for those living in urban areas.
A LITTLE RESEARCH: New drugs can slow down lung cancer and ovarian cancer
Researchers have followed the medical path of women in seven years.
Dr. Jordan said that the woman's age at the time of diagnosis, the type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases and socio-economic status also affected survival.
Older women and those who had cancer at a later stage at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
For those living in regions or remote areas of the state, the probability of dying during the study was 20 per cent higher than for those living in urban areas.
Although the study was not designed to determine why women living outside cities were more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that delayed diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment were possible factors.
"This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynaecology oncology, and they're mostly in big cities," she said.
Despite improvements in the quality of tele-health services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that an increase in the number of exit services that would enable professionals to treat women closer to home and in support programmes for people receiving treatment far from home could help.
Dr. Jordan said that, regardless of geographical location, the study found that life expectancy among women with ovarian cancer was rare, stressing the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer caser, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
