The biggest Chinese companies have united against Alibaba.
Chinese companies, among which the largest commercial real estate developer in China, the Dalian Wanda Group, and Internet giants Tencent Holdings (socinets, Messenger, etc.) and Baidu (the largest Chinese search engine), are creating a company that will compete in the online market with Alibaba.
However, catching up on the Chinese Internet miracle that has left behind even its American rivals, eBay and Amazon.com, will not be easy.
Union of the Largest
Companies are planning to invest 5 billion yuan ($814 million) in a joint venture, 70% of which will be owned by Wanda and 15% each of the Internet companies, as reported by the Wanda Group.
It is planned to register the firm in Hong Kong.
SP will integrate Baidu's search services with the popular social platform WeChat (the largest social network in China, with some 438 million users), Tencent and Wanda infrastructure.
In addition to a network of 40 luxury hotels, Wanda manages at least 49 commercial properties throughout China and 40 trading centres.
Last year, the company invested 50 billion yuan (more than $8 billion) in the construction of a film studio and a thematic entertainment park in Qindao (a city in eastern China on the coast of the Yellow Sea).
The project is expected to attract more than 1 million visitors each year and generate revenue of $960 million.
In addition, Wanda owns the American AMC Entertainment Holdings, making the company the largest cinema operator in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all its trading centres, hotels, and entertainment places with e-commerce services, which will be developed by a competitor named Alibaba.
According to Dong Ce, who will lead the new company, Wanda will be able to increase the number of e-commerce users from the current 40 million to 100 million by next year.
The new platform should become the world's largest online-to-offline platform, noting Dong Ce.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract customers on the Internet to go to regular offline stores or to buy other traditional services.
Classic examples of O2O are coupons such as Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
"O2O is the largest pie in the online business," said Wanda leader Wang Jianlin.
"There is currently no real O2O site in China, and in this situation the chances are roughly equal," he says.
The Chinese Internet market is the largest in the world, and McKinsey & Co. estimates that it will more than triple by 2015 compared to 2011, to $395 billion.
The number of Chinese Internet users has increased to 632 million, with Bloomberg reporting official statistics: it is larger than the population of any country in the world except India.
It is projected that this number will rise to 850 million by 2015.
Union of the Richest
Tencent Ma Huaten was until recently China's richest man, but according to the Bloomberg millionaire index, the founder of Alibaba, Jack Ma, had already surpassed him by $5.5 billion.
Jack Ma's condition is estimated at $21.8 billion, of which $11 billion is his share in Alibaba.
The leader of Baidu Robin Lee now ranks third among China's richest people, while Wang Jianlin of Wanda is the fourth highest ranking.
"It's very interesting to watch this battle: the three richest people join together to challenge the richer one," said Bloomberg, director of the China Center for E-Commerce Research in Hangzhou Cao Lai.
But he believes that the new company is unlikely to compete seriously with Aliba as soon as it is created: "Rim cannot be built in one day."
The fact that Alibaba is not so – simply competing not only with new companies, but also with the well-deserved leaders of the world’s Internet trade – is illustrated by the previous year’s report on Alibaba’s financial performance over the last quarter.
Alibaba is often described as a mean between eBay and Amazon.com, but from April to June the Chinese company earned more than both of its American competitors combined.
Alibaba's net profits during the period were almost double that of competitors - almost tripled on an annual basis to $1.99 billion.
"Alibaba still has great potential for generating money, largely because of its mobile applications," commented Bloomberg on the report of an analyst from Hong Kong's Arete Research Service.
According to the updated Alibaba prospectus on the US Securities and Exchange Commission website, the number of active mobile users of the company's services in July was 188 million, well above the March figure (163 million).
However, 32.8 per cent of all Alibaba transactions in the last quarter were carried out by mobile devices.
Alibaba has to name the value of its shares before IPO.
According to an average estimate of 11 analysts interviewed by Bloomberg, the company could be valued at $187 billion after selling shares.
According to Bloomberg sources, Alibaba's debut on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) could take place on September 16.
The road-show company preceding this event will begin on September 3.
Alibaba's entry into IPO is expected to be the highest in the history of NYSE and will allow the company to attract about $20 billion.
So far, the record of the US stock was held by the Visa payment system, which in 2008 made the initial placement of its shares, earning $17.9 billion.
At least half of the food in the trading networks should be Russian-made, according to the State Duma.
