WESNA prepared a cold surprise in southern Australia, bringing heavy rains and strong winds that affected flights to Adelaide Airport.
Another 5 mm rain fell on the city at 9 p.m., followed by 6.6 mm that fell on Sunday night.
The last rain was preceded by a couple of short rains with a bursting wind, including a storm that started shortly before 8 p.m. and spilled almost 4 mm in about 10 minutes.
After winter released an early spring last week, the temperature dropped again on Monday to a maximum of 15.8C in the city.
Squalid conditions are believed to have contributed to the delay in landing Virgin Airlines from Melbourne to Adelaide.
The plane was scheduled to land immediately after 7:30 p.m., but entered the wind shift - sudden changes in wind speed or direction at a short distance - and was forced to gain altitude.
Wind bursts reached 50 km/h on the ground at Adelaide Airport at that time.
The flight data showed that the aircraft had to gain altitude during its second landing, and the aircraft finally landed around 8:40 p.m.
The delay in this flight caused subsequent delays to several other flights, including the Emirates flight from Dubai and the Qantas flight from Sydney.
A maximum of 16C is projected in Adelaide on Tuesday, with a probability of one or two rains.
