Israeli children return to school after the war in the Gaza Strip
Thousands of Israeli children in the territories near the Gaza Strip went back to school on Monday after spending the summer in shelters, when rockets and landmines fell on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in the Gaza Strip remained closed while the territory was being rebuilt after the fighting.
The start of school classes brought joy and excitement to the rocket-affected settlements in southern Israel, but the signs of fighting remained fresh.
In the southern city of Ashdod, employees of Pashos kindergarten, which was hit by a rocket, removed fragments from the walls and slides before the pupils arrived.
"We're a little afraid, but we're happy to look to the future," said Ronit Bart, a resident of Kibutza Saad and an English teacher at his school.
Many children in our area really need to get back to a decent life.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Bart, said that all of a sudden she's going back to school "a little weird."
"It's been a difficult time, and we haven't left our homes at all," she said.
President Reuwen Rivlin visited Kibbutz, close to the Gaza border, to express his support.
Before the ceasefire ended the war last week, thousands of residents of border settlements, such as Saad, did not go outside or left their homes, leaving for safer areas further from the Gaza Strip to escape rocket and mortar fire.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, settlements near the Gaza border, where a 4-year-old boy was killed by a fragment of a Palestinian mine, doubt that they should return.
The Ministry of Education reported that about a dozen families had not yet returned.
Their children were sent to other schools during that time.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a city on the Gaza border, which had been hard hit by Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study hard and said, "We will do our utmost to give you knowledge and to ensure your safety."
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite truce last Tuesday.
The ceasefire agreement immediately put an end to the fighting, but key issues remained unresolved, such as Hamas's demand for the lifting of the Egyptian-Israeli blockade on Gaza and the opening of airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its arms and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers who died in the war.
A new phase of proximity talks is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
More than 2,100 Palestinians were killed in the war, three quarters of them civilians, and at least 494 children were estimated by the Palestinian side and the United Nations.
Israel contests these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; despite this, it has not provided substantial evidence to substantiate this allegation.
On the Israeli side, 66 soldiers and six civilians, including one Thai worker, were killed.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gaza fighters fired 4,591 rockets and mortars at Israeli cities, mostly in the south of the country.
Meanwhile, the Israeli army launched more than 5,000 air and other attacks.
Thousands of homes in the Gaza Strip have been damaged and destroyed as a result of Israeli attacks, and an estimated 250,000 people have taken refuge in more than 100 schools, which have been transformed into shelters.
Because tens of thousands of people were still in shelters and fighting continued, education officials postponed the start of the school year last week.
“I hope that the school will soon open so that we can complete our education, like the children of the world and Jewish children”, said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in a school in Gaza.
According to the popular criterion, real estate prices showed the largest winter rise in seven years.
