RP Data figures show that in Sydney housing prices have risen by 16.1 per cent over the past year, compared with 11.7 per cent in Melbourne.
The next largest markets were Adelaide, Brisbein, and Darwin, where prices increased from 5 to 6 per cent on average.
At the other end of the scale was Canberra, which was marked by government spending cuts, where prices rose by only 1.4 per cent per year.
Mr. Lawless said that now that spring has begun, there will be an increase in the number of real estate items placed on the market over the next few months, which will be a "real test" for the market.
“Bearing in mind the current high rate of auction sales, the overall high rate of sales and the current low interest rate conditions, it is likely that the cost of housing will rise in the next three months,” he said.
