State and local tax accounts for companies throughout the country increased moderately last year, when economic recovery accelerated, according to a new study published last week, and a company in the Washington Zone is no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland, and Virginia together paid $27.6 billion to the state and local treasury in fiscal year 2013, 3.8 per cent more than the $26.6 billion collected in 2012.
The tax burden on business by state and local level increased by 4.3 per cent last year, to $671 billion, from 3.9 per cent a year earlier, and this was the third consecutive year of growth after successive years of declining accounts in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes increased faster, 4.3 per cent than local taxes, 3.9 per cent, according to a study conducted by a professional service firm, Ernst & Young, and the State Tax Center, the tax policy group.
More than half of the county's tax revenue, 56 per cent, comes from business taxes, while 36 per cent of Maryland's tax revenue comes from firms.
Virginia, with 28 per cent, has the lowest tax revenue, proportionally, from entrepreneurs.
To a large extent, the increase in tax revenues is due to a return to the old value of companies' real estate, researchers say that it raised real estate taxes by 3.7 per cent this year after three consecutive years of growth of less than 1 per cent.
While large states such as California, New York, and Texas account for a large share of this revenue, the same seems to be happening in the Washington Zone.
Companies in the county, Maryland, and Virginia together paid $10 billion in state and local real estate taxes last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012, an increase of 4.2 per cent over the previous year.
However, the observed return on real estate does not have any similar effect on the increase in state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where real estate taxes barely exceed one fifth of companies' tax accounts.
Virginia and D.C. companies pay about half of State and local tax accounts in the form of real estate taxes.
"What's going on in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around D.C., is owned either by the government or by a non-profit organization that doesn't pay real estate taxes," said Douglas Lindholm, CEO of the State Tax Center.
Maryland therefore has to rely much more on income taxes, for example, to pay for the same services as in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be entirely attributed to the re-establishment of the real estate market.
The income of entrepreneurs also seems to be on the right track, according to these data.
Companies in the region declared a state-level corporate income tax of $2.3 billion, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland collected $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, the largest in the region.
While trends are in the same direction, the tax burden of entrepreneurs at the local level does not increase at the same rate in all three locations.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was the same as the national average, 4.3 per cent, while the growth rate in Maryland was significantly faster, 4.9 per cent.
In Virginia alone, tax revenues rose below the average of 4.1 per cent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate) at 6 per cent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 per cent, compared with a relatively high rate of 9.975 per cent in the county.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year showed that Virginia had lower taxes for state and local entrepreneurs and, in general, a more favourable climate for business taxes than Maryland.
The county was not assessed in the study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from her neighbour from the south.
North Carolina has recently signed legislation reducing the corporate rate this year from 6.9 per cent to 6 per cent, as in Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 per cent next year.
