Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington Zone seem to be feeling better and thus paying more state and local taxes, according to a recent study.
Business taxes paid by small business owners in the form of an individual income tax - a transition structure that accommodates most small firms - in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia - increased by 20 per cent last year to $2.4 billion, with a much higher rate of growth than taxes for entrepreneurs in general.
Researchers say that the trend and increase in business tax revenue across the country is likely to continue this year, with turnover tax revenues in state and local governments increasing by 6.2 per cent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared with the same period last year.
