The deputies suggested that the Personal Data Act should be expedited.
If the initiative is successful, Russians will not be able to store data on servers abroad as of 1 January 2015
A draft law has been introduced in the State Duma to extend the date of entry into force of the already adopted Russian Personal Data Act from 1 September 2016 to 1 January 2015.
The initiative is part of the legislative framework of the lower house.
The authors were members of the State Duma, Vadim Mán, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Yevgeny Fedorov (Uniform Russia), Vladimir Parahin (Justified Russia) and Alexander Yushchenko (KPRF).
This change, in the view of the proponents, will help to ensure faster and more effective protection of the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to the preservation of personal data and the privacy of correspondence in information and telecommunications networks.
The Act, whose entry into force is rushed by parliamentarians, requires Russians to keep their personal data on the territory of the Russian Federation processed through the Internet.
It also makes it mandatory to record, systematize, accumulate, store, refine and extract personal data from citizens of the Russian Federation in databases located in the Russian Federation, as well as to indicate the location of such databases.
In addition, the law gives Roskomnadzor the right to restrict access to information processed in violation of Russian personal data legislation by a court decision.
The Act also proposes the creation of so-called “blacklists” of offending websites, an automated information system called the “Register of violators of the rights of personal data subjects”.
This law was passed by the State Duma in the summer.
The draft was sponsored by Andrei Lugova and Vadim Malone of LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko of CRCF.
Mán and Yushchenko are also among the sponsors of the current bill on the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who don't have data centers in the Russian Federation will have to pay rent.
Commenting on the bill introduced today in the State Duma, Leonid Levine stated that he saw no problem in moving the date of entry into force of the Personal Data Protection Act.
According to him, those companies that by 1 January 2015 would not have their own Russian personal data repositories on the territory of the Russian Federation would be able to rent them, for example, from “Rostelcom”, which has repeatedly said that they are willing to rent their servers and are already providing their servers, from Mail Group, from Western companies that are now providing their servers.”
“In addition, there are several independent data centres willing to cooperate in this field”, he added.
“If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to work in the territory of the Russian Federation, I see no problem – they will have technological accommodation,” Levin summarized.
Disputed Bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law, the Russian Electronic Communications Association feared that if the draft law were adopted, Russians would no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
These include online booking services for airlines and hotels.
According to the association, “the draft law deprives the subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation - of the right to dispose of their own data by making it imperative that their recording, systematization, etc., should be provided only in databases located in the territory of the Russian Federation”.
The RAEC statement emphasizes that a more effective measure would be to establish a mechanism to inform the user of where the recording takes place and to systematize its personal data.
In such a case, it would be up to the individual to decide on the territory in which the acts would be carried out.
The adoption of similar bills on the “localization” of personal data in other countries has led to the abandonment of global services and significant economic losses.
