The sharpness of the situation is that this step is planned because of the small and medium-sized banks that distribute such certificates, and will be affected by it, Sberbank and the Bank of Moscow, which are estimated by ACV to control 98 per cent of the relevant market.
The Bank of Moscow is estimated by the Agency to account for about 3.5 per cent.
The problem, explained by the AAC, is that the customers of a small bank that bought such a certificate, if his licence is withdrawn, try to obtain money from the AAC.
Some depositors, lacking financial literacy and buying bearer savings certificates, may assume that their investments are insured.
The well-founded lack of insurance payments for these certificates, if the bank ' s licence is revoked, could lead to misunderstanding and social tensions.
In the agency's practice, there have been cases in which bearers of bearer certificates have sought to recover insurance compensation through a court of law”, stated the AAC.
The problem is, of course, bogus.
After all, no one will pay the buyers of certificates, since they have no legal right to compensation from the State.
Had it been that the instrument was not insured by the ASA, it would have been banned from the metal accounts in which the funds of the citizens were recorded in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
These accounts are not included in the deposit insurance system either, but their existence has not yet been attempted.
It is likely that bearer certificates are a very convenient security that can actually act as a quasi-dengue.
However, their movement is virtually uncontrollable: any client of a bank can buy a certificate, hand it over to any citizen, and before cashing it can be replaced by many owners.
It is not by accident that the bill stipulates that a savings certificate must necessarily be the name of the security that must be kept in the depositary.
And in order to sweeten the pill to banks, such certificates are allowed to be issued without the possibility of early repayment.
That is to say, the equivalent of an irrevocable contribution that bankers have long dreamed of.
