The hearty expression of a face is biologically universal to mankind, and every organ and muscle group involved in its creation is not an accident, but an additional means of expressing power and threat, learned by Australian and U.S. scientists.
They described their discoveries in Evolution and Human Behavior magazine, and they can be summarized in a press release from the University of California in Santa Barbara.
The angry expression of the face - the eyebrows bent down into a thin line of lips, the bloated nostrils - is the same in all cultures, and even the children born blind and never seen it, is noted by Aaron Sell, the lead author of the study.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists have found that this emotion has emerged to effectively manage disputes during conflict.
The more physical harm one person can cause to another, the more he is able to dictate his conditions, and he communicates them with anger.
Researchers have also found evidence of another hypothesis: physically powerful people are more likely to be angry and to use their hands, to impose conditions that are unfavourable to others, and to prefer violent methods to resolve conflicts peacefully.
Based on the fact that anger is primarily an “emotion of bargaining”, scientists have decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that create the angry expression of a face must represent an angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interviewer - and thus force him to accept its terms as soon as possible in order to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, researchers modeled on the computer faces where each of the seven elements of the angry face was present or missing, and showed them to informants.
Although the lower eyebrows or the forward chin alone did not make the face evil, the more powerful man-like face of the study was unanimously accepted.
Man’s anger, like that of animals, is a threat: an exaggeration of self - power that compels consent and submission.
A man blowes his nostrils and presses his lips for the same purpose as a frog that inflates, or a baboon who shows his fangs.
Anger is “launched” by the respondent's refusal to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form most effectively showing the opposite side the consequences of the refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of an angry face is arbitrary, all of them express the same thing," said anthropologist John Toubi.
The Ministry of Communications has offered 250 million rubles from Crimea Radio and Television.
The Ministry of Communications has proposed that 250 million roubles be allocated from the federal budget to the autonomous non-profit organization Crimea Tele-radiology Company in 2014.
This is stated in a draft government decree prepared by an agency which was consulted by Lena.ru.
According to the Explanatory Note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed “to cover the costs of creating conditions for extensive information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of a modern information space in the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the acquisition of equipment”.
In particular, it is proposed to upgrade the studio unit, the video walls and the central hardware and video server for the money allocated.
The acquisition of a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter is also planned.
In addition, the company will pay for the fibre-optic link (VOLS) and the maintenance of the energy system.
Grants will be provided within the federal budget allocated to the Ministry of Communications.
The State broadcasting company Crimea was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, more than 75 per cent of the territory of the peninsula has been covered by television and radio.
In 2011, Crimea Television received a licence to broadcast in digital format.
